headline: Democratic rivals pile on Elizabeth Warren at presidential debate
subHeadline: Candidates ease up on Joe Biden, focus on Sen. Warren during televised Democratic debate; reaction and analysis on 'The Five.'

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello everybody. I'm Jesse Watters along with Emily Compagno, Juan Williams, Dana Perino, and Greg. It's 5 o'clock in New York City, and this is "The Five." It was a night of far-left policies at the Democratic debate. And if you didn't catch it, no worries, we've got you covered on all the low lights, including the absurd calls for gun confiscation, taking away your health care, and raising your taxes. The moderates of the group struggled to keep up with all the radical positions. Take a look.

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN, DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.sentences: I'm the only one on the stage that has gotten anything really big done.

utterances.speaker: BERNIE SANDERS, DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.sentences: you've also got (INAUDIBLE) this is a good friend. You've got the disastrous war in Iraq done.

utterances.speaker: ELIZABETH WARREN, DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.sentences: I have made clear what my principles are here, and that is cost will go up for the wealthy and for big corporations.

utterances.speaker: BIDEN
utterances.sentences: The plan is going to cost at least $30 trillion over ten years.

utterances.speaker: SANDERS
utterances.sentences: I'm a little bit tired, I must say. Our people defending a system which is dysfunctional, which is cruel.

utterances.speaker: WARREN
utterances.sentences: Why is it -- does everyone else on this stage think it's more important to protect billionaires than it is to invest in an entire generation of America?

utterances.speaker: AMY KLOBUCHAR, DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.sentences: I want to give a reality check here to Elizabeth, because no one on this stage wants to protect billionaires. Not even the billionaire wants to protect billionaires.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Liz Warren became a major target as her rivals went on the attack.

utterances.speaker: BETO O'ROURKE, DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.sentences: I think that Senator Warren is more focused on being punitive or pitting some parts of the country against the other.

utterances.speaker: BIDEN
utterances.sentences: Well, the senator said she's being vague on the issue of -- actually, both of being vague on the issue of Medicare for all.

utterances.speaker: PETE BUTTIGIEG
utterances.sentences: A yes or no question that didn't get a yes or no answer. Your signature, senator, is to have a plan for everything except this. No plan has been laid out to explain how a multitrillion dollar hole is supposed to get filled in.

utterances.speaker: KLOBUCHAR
utterances.sentences: At least, Bernie is being honest here and saying how he's going to pay for this, and that taxes are going to go up. And I'm sorry, Elizabeth, but you have not said that. The difference between a plan and a pipe dream is something that you can actually get done.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Wow. And another big blow to Warren's campaign, three members of the far-left squad are now going to be endorsing Bernie Sanders. All right, Greg, what struck you last night?

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Well, jeez. Where to start? I think the winners in my mind were Mayor Pete, Amy Klobuchar, kind of goofy but really sharp, and I disagree with almost everything he says, but Bernie showed that he's had the energy. I mean, that dude just had a heart attack and he had more energy than everybody there. But while I was watching it, I just felt like I was in line at the budget rent-a-car counter, and everybody -- all their cars are late or they didn't get the caprice with the convertible, and they're just --

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Complaining?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: And they're complaining and they're -- I'll take anything, but they're in front of you. Beto was correct for once in his life about Liz being punitive. She -- every time she sees a successful person, she doesn't see the hard work that they do. She sees them as somebody that we can take from. She's basically -- her mentality fueled the worst governments of 20th century.  It's bureaucrat looking at people trying to achieve and taking everything they have. Buttigieg did a great job on Beto. He was like the -- your uncle who's a veteran at Thanksgiving dinner telling that college freshman who's saying Americans are imperialist and he says, shut up and eat your mashed potatoes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I actually think we have that, so let's watch.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: You just made it clear that you don't know how this is actually going to take weapons off the streets.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Let's follow their inspiration and lead, and not be limited by the polls and the consultants and the focus group --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: -- to do what's right.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Mayor Buttigieg?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: The promise in the polls -- the problem is the policy.  And I don't need lessons from you on courage, political or personal.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: All right, yes. So Mayor Pete had a nice scrappy night. Last night, Juan, he's definitely now -- I think catapulted himself into a top tier position. He raised a million dollars in 24 hours. He had a pretty good night. Who do you think went up and who do you think went down after last night?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: The big take away is Elizabeth Warren takes the lead. Everybody is going after her. Everybody respects her. They have arguments on her grounds in terms of attacking her on health care.   And I don't think she ever answered the question --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: No.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: OK. But it was her territory, and also, on the billionaire business, the idea of taxing the rich. So, again, it's all taken place on her terms. I think Biden was OK to flat for me, but I don't think he lost any ground. The question is whether or not people like Amy Klobuchar, Pete Buttigieg were able to gain sufficiently that if Biden were to collapse or go away for some reason, they would then occupy this middle lane, which is the moderate lane.  But, again, I don't agree that they did anything at the moment to either regain some of the loss -- support to that we've seen Elizabeth Warren gain in terms of her rise, or to knock out Joe Biden. I just don't see it. I think that for Buttigieg, especially, but also for Amy Klobuchar, the question would be can you attract anybody who is a black voter? I don't know.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I don't know. I think Warren, though, is -- and, you know, I think this is why I think that she comes out of this debate the winner.  She is a populist. You know how Trump is a populist on the right? She's a populist on the left. And populism -- we live in an age when populism sells, and I think she's doing a great job.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: But then, why did AOC endorse the true first populist, Bernie Sanders, and not Liz?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Because, you know what? He just had a heart attack, as you pointed out, Greg. And I think there's a lot of people who are saying, you know, you may not make it all the way, but this is the point where if you need a boost, you know, we're going to throw you a life support at this point.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I don't think the squad endorsed Bernie because he had a heart attack. I think it's because, ideologically, they believe that Bernie is the revolutionary.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: They're the ones -- he is actually the pure socialist. He's been working at this. AOC had endorsed him before. She worked on his campaign, right? And I think that -- I think that they know that -- like, in their minds, Elizabeth Warren is less likable than Bernie. But they also think that she actually won't be the change, right? Remember Obama was like, I'll be the change? I don't think that they really believe that Elizabeth Warren --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: She'll leave you with change.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Tax and --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Liz Warren, as Juan mentioned, did struggle to account for how she was going to pay for a $30 trillion Medicare for all without raising middle-class taxes. Do you think she was unsteady on her feet? Because it looks to me like she couldn't answer the question once again.

utterances.speaker: EMILY COMPAGNO, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Yeah, I don't know if unsteady is the word I'll use. I think she was evasive and just failed, right? And she failed on the opportunity to actually answer clearly. I think that when she was attacked by the majority of the other candidates on stage, it really illustrated more in those moments about them than her, with the exception of her failure to account for who is paying for Medicare, or who would pay for Medicare for all. And also, her foreign policy incompetence, which he talked about pulling all of the troops away from the Middle East, she ignored the eight bases we have there.  And I think the situation right now in Syria is really illustrating to voters that we need a commander-in-chief that has that type of foreign policy competence. And that's why, in my opinion, Biden and Mayor Pete shown in that specific regard which brings me to who I think the winner was last night, which was totally Mayor Pete by a landslide. I think he came out swinging, but it didn't seem inauthentic. It was the same amazing orator, but more in sync. And he pivoted a lot of the topics to I think a better perspective for the force, for the trees, 538 has him the highest increase now of Democratic voters that are switching over. And he shot past Kamala. And I also think that he's attracting the never- Trumpers. My loser, Tulsi, a hundred percent.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Oh, Greg, do you agree with that? Because I think Tulsi had a few very powerful lines --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, I thought the regime change thing was good. I would disagree. I would say that the loser was Castro who completely disappeared. I think that --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Beto, also.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Beto was a loser. But you point about Mayor Pete, which I agree, before he was always kind of expressing his articulation as something impress. But now he took his skills and he used it to persuade people, which I thought was like a shift. And that he made -- it made him seem like he was the only -- or one of the three adults there.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I like that style that you pointed out. He dump it down a little bit because all these people on the stage, half of them are senators, and they speak like senators and they're not connecting. And I think Mayor Pete did a good job of connecting by speaking in a little more of a blunt fashion.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, there's two people that we haven't even mentioned in all of this in the A-block, and that is Cory Booker, the senator from New Jersey.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Mr. Nice Guy.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: He's the peacemaker.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: The peacemaker, right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Blessed are the peacemakers. And Tom Steyer who was the billionaire that was on stage. He was looking directly into the camera. He had that tie that is just like, what? And I didn't know that he wears the same tie every day, but he has five of them.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: He does?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It's actually a tattoo.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: So, I think, the fact that he had made the debate stage totally irrelevant.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He makes Adam Schiff, you know, look conscious.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You know, I think Amy Klobucher had a real good night.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Me, too.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I don't want us to run by her, because I think it's so interesting. She was directly taking on Elizabeth Warren in a way that suggested to me that she sees Warren as someone that she can beat in a straight on debate. But the whole business about how are you going to pay, let me just say, I think she's been very clear about how she wants to pay for health care in the country, which is she wants to impose a tax on the super rich. I don't think there's any question about that. It's just that she won't admit that it may mean that you also increase some taxes on the middle class. Her argument, of course, is overall cost, deductible, premiums, will go down.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I think the best ticket from that group is Klobuchar, Mayor Pete.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, but remember --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: No, no, no. Greg, on a bumper sticker, you can't have Buttigieg and Klobuchar.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Klobuchar and Buttigieg.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Either one.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Coming up, Joe Biden tries to explain away the Ukraine controversy. Plus, tempers flying in the Capital as we're learning of an explosive meeting between the president, Pelosi and Chuck Schumer, breaking news out of Washington, D.C., up next.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Former Vice President Joe Biden walked through his son's Ukraine controversy practically unscaled last night as debate moderators lobe multiple softballs questions. Watch this.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: President Trump has falsely accused your son of doing something wrong while serving on a company board in Ukraine. I want to point out, there's no evidence of wrongdoing by either one of you.

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN, FORMER U.S. VICE PRESIDENT
utterances.sentences: My son did nothing wrong. I did nothing wrong. I carried out the policy of the United States government in rooting out corruption in Ukraine. But I wanted to make a point about -- my son's statement speaks for itself. What we have to do now is focus on Donald Trump. He's going after me, because he knows if I get the nomination, I will beat him like a drum.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: And from bad to worse, Joe Biden has reportedly spent more than he raised in the third quarter of 2019. Juan, I would like to start with you. So notwithstanding the intro and the lack of follow-up that Anderson Cooper displayed, he did ask Joe Biden, pointblank, if it's not OK for the president to have his children be in foreign business dealings, why is it OK for the vice president? I put that question to you.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, I think he answered it pretty clearly. He said he didn't have the discussions. Now, we've seen reporting that in any case there was some discussion, but he said no, and he said the son said no, and he says he stands by what the son had to say, which was awkward on the day of the debate for the son to come out. But, anyway, that's what happened. And he says he stands by what the son had to say, and he did nothing wrong. Anderson Cooper, by the way, I don't know why you're picking on him. It was a false accusation that was made against Biden, and now you have a situation where people are saying, oh, Joe Biden respond to this, respond to this. Well, he just said, flat out, hey, I'm not playing that game and I appreciated it. I think that he was strong not to play somebody else's game. The real debate today, it seems to me is up on the Hill where you have -- I think it was 130 Republicans voting against Trump on the pull-out from -- I mean, that's the real argument. That and the --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: How about the debate, Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, I'm saying, that's what -- it's not about -- this stuff about Biden is just a false --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know what's really bad for Joe Biden right now? President -- the former President Obama just endorsed Justin Trudeau before he endorsed Joe Biden who is, right now, he's been seen running to Walmart buying shoe polish.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: All right, Jesse, if Biden makes it to the general is this going to be the clip that haunts him that President Trump pulled is that you can't even answer the question.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I don't know if he's going to make it to the general. But I do remember in 2016 when CNN moderators would argue with the Republicans running for president. And now, they just team up and let them say whatever they want. You know what reminds me of? When someone was falsely accused of something without any evidence? Donald Trump was falsely accused of being a Russian colluder without any evidence. CNN never has actually said that Donald Trump was falsely accused without any evidence after two and a half years. So, that is funny and that's a perfect example of media bias. Also interesting, let's just switch the names because I'm going to start doing this just for fun. Imagine the minute Trump selected, Don Jr. gets a sweetheart deal on the board of a Ukrainian gas company, and then the president demands the guy investigating the corrupt Ukrainian gas company is fired and withhold aids, and then the guy gets fired. And then when they ask about him about it, you guys talked about it, they say no. We never brought it up. And by the way, I was just doing my job. Look elsewhere.  Do you think the media would accept Donald Trump's and Don Jr. explanation for that? Absolutely not, and that's why it's so crooked. And the fact that Biden comes out and tells CNN that his job in Ukraine was to root out corruption, OK? Well, then your son goes and joins the board of the most corrupt gas company in Ukraine? They fire the prosecutor looking into the corrupt gas company. And, as a matter of fact, corruption in Ukraine increased under Joe Biden's watch. That's why Zelensky was elected. He ran on an anti-corruption platform.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Wow, Alice in Wonderland, you've got nothing on Jesse Watters. Way down the rabbit hole. You make stuff up --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: What did I say that was wrong?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, what did you say that was wrong?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Can you just do it later?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: The fundraising thing, right. So he has spent more money than he has raise. And other candidates -- I think four other candidates have more cash on hand than he does. So he's got to figure out a way to step on the gas or reduce his burn rate. I do think that last night in the debate that one of the things that Democrats have learned is that attacking each other on stage doesn't work, or at least it doesn't work for long. Kamala Harris went after Joe Biden in that first debate, and she was popular for about 26 hours. Julian Castro went after Biden, and that last for 26 hours. So they're very happy to allow Donald Trump to be the one that beats up on Joe Biden, because then they don't have to. I do think for Biden, he could pull a Newt Gingrich and just go after the moderators, Juan. I think you'll remember that. And then that becomes the story, like, I've had it with you. I can't take it anymore. The other thing is Biden doesn't do any one-on-one interviews, so there's not a lot of ways to be able to dig in a little bit deeper. I mean, his son did an interview before he did.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Interesting. Greg, you feel so strongly about media bias.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I do. Thank you for bringing that up, Emily.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Thanks for noticing.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. I think that Anderson -- that was a pretty soft question for him. I would say it was up there with, maybe, you know, giving questions to a candidate. But the thing is, Biden, I just -- it's not if he drops out, it's when. To me, this grumpy smile that he has, and that orchestrated attempt at arousing climax at the end, you could see it coming and you felt that the sympathy clap was like a nurse -- you know, clapping for gramps because he finished the peas. I think that -- I think that he's misunderstanding the moment. He's seeing this as politics as usual and -- this moment has passed him.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: It's not 2012.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It's not 2012.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: I felt like in that moment he was a dad, and we saw him as that -- in the other side of trauma, and so it made sense that he's basically, like, I will never disparage my son on the stage. But then it was a failed opportunity for him to act presidential and taking it a step further and pivoting and saying and here, let me tell you about my ethics plan that I have which he's talked about.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: But by doing that admits that it was wrong.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I just want to remind everybody, Joe Biden remains either in the lead or tied, basically, with Elizabeth Warren.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Hillary Clinton was once was.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: All right, up next, tempers flying in the nation's capital and the meeting between President Trump, Nancy Pelosi, and Chuck Schumer. This all just went down, we have the breaking details next.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Breaking news out of Washington. An explosive meeting in Washington as Nancy Pelosi and Chuck Schumer reportedly walked out of a meeting with President Trump, the topic at hand, Syria. According to top Democrats, Trump called Pelosi a third-rate politician. Here to break it all down, Kevin Corke. Kevin, earlier today, I said, well, we'll get back to you if anything big happens at the White House, and here you are. Tell us what happened.

utterances.speaker: KEVIN CORKE, FOX NEWS CORRESPONDENT
utterances.sentences: And there you have it, right? Well done, and that's a Colorado connection, get it done for you there on THE FIVE. Let me just say this, the White House says the president was measured, decisive, and factual. They called the walkout by Nancy Pelosi baffling, but not surprising. As for Pelosi, herself, well, her colleagues say the president was downright insulting. He was having a meltdown. Here's what Chuck Schumer said about it not long ago.

utterances.speaker: SEN. CHUCK SCHUMER (D-NY)
utterances.sentences: It was insulting, particularly to the Speaker.  She kept her cool completely. But he called her a third-rate politician. He said that there are communists involved and you guys might like that. I mean, this was not a dialogue. It was sort of a diatribe, a nasty diatribe not focused on the facts.

utterances.speaker: CORKE
utterances.sentences: Fair and balance, that's the Democrats' side of things. On the GOP side, they say the Speaker didn't really have an intention of listening or contributing to this issue. She just wanted to have her way. Here's Mr. McCarthy.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: You see a pattern of behavior with Speaker Nancy Pelosi. She storms out of another meeting, trying to make it unproductive. The other Democrats, they actually had a very productive meeting.

utterances.speaker: CORKE
utterances.sentences: And you probably know this, Dana, there was actually another meeting scheduled for tomorrow about Syria. That meeting has been canceled, we are told. And given what happened today, probably not the worst idea. Dana?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right. Thanks, Kevin Corke at the White House. You have a third-rate politician as a compliment?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, somebody called me a third-rate -- it's better to be a first-rate politician. A first-rate politician, you're just a phony jack ass. But like -- Trump is a 12th rate politician. He doesn't even register, so it's actually a compliment. Look, this is obviously the worst thing that has ever happened since yesterday when the worst thing that ever happened had happened, and then before that. The fact is, every day with these people, it's the worst thing. Their hair is on fire all the time. You can see it from space. They're smoky heads are flaming. I don't care about it anymore. You can disagree with them about this. A lot of people do, you know. But the fact is this is who Trump is. He's America's cabdriver. He believes that -- like, if you ask him, if you go - - driving a cab and the cab driver go, this Middle East business it's a bunch of crap. What are we doing there? We're there for 20, 40 years. No one gets anything done. It's terrible. That's our president. What's wrong with that?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, I tell you that's scary.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No, it's actually --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, because he want -- you want somebody as your leader. Someone who protects the flock, someone who's wise, and someone --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He wants American troops out of harms way.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: In fact, he's creating more risk. Why do you think -- wait a second. Normally, on this show, we have sort of debate about things that are Republican, Democrat, conservative, liberal, libertarian, whatever. But, Greg, this is like 129 Republicans today voting with Democrats, including all of the House Republican leadership, to say the president is wrong, putting us Americans right here at home at risk, ISIS people being released to the world without any control.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I think they have his best interest in mind in the criticism and the pushback.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: For me, I think it's like one of those things in the swamp when there's bipartisan consensus to stay in Syria, and then outside and the rest of the country there's consensus to get the hell out of Syria. That's the disconnect. And the president is looking at both parties who've made a mess in the Middle East. You've got the Arab spring. You've had genocides. You've had wars. You've got everything going on, a migration crisis, weapons of mass destruction, and he's gonna say, you know what, enough. Let's let the Turks fight the Kurds fight the Syrians fight the Iranians, and let's get the hell out of here.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Except for now he is trying to figure out that diplomacy piece, which I think that you could agree. Let's get out. But maybe just trying to figure out a way to do it that is a little bit less bloodshed.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Thank you, Ms. Perino.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: People are dying in Syria and Turkey and everywhere, including our--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: And New York City, by the way.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: And my tax dollars are paying the salary for those people who are sitting there and storming out of meetings and calling themselves insulting in front of the cameras like it's two little kids or three kids. No, he didn't. No, he did it, mom. I don't care. I want them to figure it out, because these are high stakes, in my opinion. And as a taxpayer, these are lives. So, I'm so sick of this civil war happening and the insulting from the coequal branch of government. We pay them and we put our faith in them to hold these offices to come to a consensus. This is getting out of control, in my opinion.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But how do you argue with the cab driver, Emily? If that cab driver is saying, no, just get out.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You're missing the point.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: That cab driver has been driving--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You're deliberately missing the point. All right. So, here's the debate that's going on that we saw today. You have a group of people that see the potential to hurt Trump in this thing. And so, they're building it up. Right. This is another thing. Remember, last week it was impeachment. Now, it's this. They'll find something else. So, I view a lot of this with this fight with suspicion. And there is actually a legitimate point that Trump is making and has been making for almost 20 years.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But what I'm saying to you is that the Republicans have largely stayed with President Trump in opposition to the impeachment. But we see something different here, Greg and I think it suggests, this is far more serious.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Can I make a historical comparison. You don't have to go back too far to when President Obama decided not to enforce the red line. And I don't know what the number was, but I bet it was at least 130 Democrats who said President Obama that is a terrible idea. You had three Cabinet secretaries, Clinton, Podesta and Gates all write books saying, and Carrie.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All saying that was not a good decision. That was a terrible decision, because it led to ISIS. So, it's not like this is unprecedented.

utterances.speaker: AMY KLOBUCHAR, DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: I want to give a reality check here to Elizabeth, because no one on this stage wants to protect billionaires. Not even the billionaire wants to protect billionaires.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Liz Warren became a major target as her rivals went on the attack.

utterances.speaker: BETO O'ROURKE, DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: I think that Senator Warren is more focused on being punitive or pitting some parts of the country against the other.

utterances.speaker: BIDEN
utterances.utterance: Well, the senator said she's being vague on the issue of -- actually, both of being vague on the issue of Medicare for all.

utterances.speaker: PETE BUTTIGIEG
utterances.utterance: A yes or no question that didn't get a yes or no answer. Your signature, senator, is to have a plan for everything except this. No plan has been laid out to explain how a multitrillion dollar hole is supposed to get filled in.

utterances.speaker: KLOBUCHAR
utterances.utterance: At least, Bernie is being honest here and saying how he's going to pay for this, and that taxes are going to go up. And I'm sorry, Elizabeth, but you have not said that. The difference between a plan and a pipe dream is something that you can actually get done.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Wow. And another big blow to Warren's campaign, three members of the far-left squad are now going to be endorsing Bernie Sanders. All right, Greg, what struck you last night?

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Well, jeez. Where to start? I think the winners in my mind were Mayor Pete, Amy Klobuchar, kind of goofy but really sharp, and I disagree with almost everything he says, but Bernie showed that he's had the energy. I mean, that dude just had a heart attack and he had more energy than everybody there. But while I was watching it, I just felt like I was in line at the budget rent-a-car counter, and everybody -- all their cars are late or they didn't get the caprice with the convertible, and they're just --

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Complaining?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: And they're complaining and they're -- I'll take anything, but they're in front of you. Beto was correct for once in his life about Liz being punitive. She -- every time she sees a successful person, she doesn't see the hard work that they do. She sees them as somebody that we can take from. She's basically -- her mentality fueled the worst governments of 20th century. It's bureaucrat looking at people trying to achieve and taking everything they have. Buttigieg did a great job on Beto. He was like the -- your uncle who's a veteran at Thanksgiving dinner telling that college freshman who's saying Americans are imperialist and he says, shut up and eat your mashed potatoes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I actually think we have that, so let's watch.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: You just made it clear that you don't know how this is actually going to take weapons off the streets.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Let's follow their inspiration and lead, and not be limited by the polls and the consultants and the focus group --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: -- to do what's right.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Mayor Buttigieg?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: The promise in the polls -- the problem is the policy. And I don't need lessons from you on courage, political or personal.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right, yes. So Mayor Pete had a nice scrappy night. Last night, Juan, he's definitely now -- I think catapulted himself into a top tier position. He raised a million dollars in 24 hours. He had a pretty good night. Who do you think went up and who do you think went down after last night?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: The big take away is Elizabeth Warren takes the lead. Everybody is going after her. Everybody respects her. They have arguments on her grounds in terms of attacking her on health care. And I don't think she ever answered the question --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK. But it was her territory, and also, on the billionaire business, the idea of taxing the rich. So, again, it's all taken place on her terms. I think Biden was OK to flat for me, but I don't think he lost any ground. The question is whether or not people like Amy Klobuchar, Pete Buttigieg were able to gain sufficiently that if Biden were to collapse or go away for some reason, they would then occupy this middle lane, which is the moderate lane. But, again, I don't agree that they did anything at the moment to either regain some of the loss -- support to that we've seen Elizabeth Warren gain in terms of her rise, or to knock out Joe Biden. I just don't see it. I think that for Buttigieg, especially, but also for Amy Klobuchar, the question would be can you attract anybody who is a black voter? I don't know.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I don't know. I think Warren, though, is -- and, you know, I think this is why I think that she comes out of this debate the winner. She is a populist. You know how Trump is a populist on the right? She's a populist on the left. And populism -- we live in an age when populism sells, and I think she's doing a great job.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But then, why did AOC endorse the true first populist, Bernie Sanders, and not Liz?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Because, you know what? He just had a heart attack, as you pointed out, Greg. And I think there's a lot of people who are saying, you know, you may not make it all the way, but this is the point where if you need a boost, you know, we're going to throw you a life support at this point.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I don't think the squad endorsed Bernie because he had a heart attack. I think it's because, ideologically, they believe that Bernie is the revolutionary.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: They're the ones -- he is actually the pure socialist. He's been working at this. AOC had endorsed him before. She worked on his campaign, right? And I think that -- I think that they know that -- like, in their minds, Elizabeth Warren is less likable than Bernie. But they also think that she actually won't be the change, right? Remember Obama was like, I'll be the change? I don't think that they really believe that Elizabeth Warren --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: She'll leave you with change.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Tax and --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Liz Warren, as Juan mentioned, did struggle to account for how she was going to pay for a $30 trillion Medicare for all without raising middle-class taxes. Do you think she was unsteady on her feet? Because it looks to me like she couldn't answer the question once again.

utterances.speaker: EMILY COMPAGNO, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Yeah, I don't know if unsteady is the word I'll use. I think she was evasive and just failed, right? And she failed on the opportunity to actually answer clearly. I think that when she was attacked by the majority of the other candidates on stage, it really illustrated more in those moments about them than her, with the exception of her failure to account for who is paying for Medicare, or who would pay for Medicare for all. And also, her foreign policy incompetence, which he talked about pulling all of the troops away from the Middle East, she ignored the eight bases we have there. And I think the situation right now in Syria is really illustrating to voters that we need a commander-in-chief that has that type of foreign policy competence. And that's why, in my opinion, Biden and Mayor Pete shown in that specific regard which brings me to who I think the winner was last night, which was totally Mayor Pete by a landslide. I think he came out swinging, but it didn't seem inauthentic. It was the same amazing orator, but more in sync. And he pivoted a lot of the topics to I think a better perspective for the force, for the trees, 538 has him the highest increase now of Democratic voters that are switching over. And he shot past Kamala. And I also think that he's attracting the never- Trumpers. My loser, Tulsi, a hundred percent.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, Greg, do you agree with that? Because I think Tulsi had a few very powerful lines --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, I thought the regime change thing was good. I would disagree. I would say that the loser was Castro who completely disappeared. I think that --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Beto, also.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Beto was a loser. But you point about Mayor Pete, which I agree, before he was always kind of expressing his articulation as something impress. But now he took his skills and he used it to persuade people, which I thought was like a shift. And that he made -- it made him seem like he was the only -- or one of the three adults there.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I like that style that you pointed out. He dump it down a little bit because all these people on the stage, half of them are senators, and they speak like senators and they're not connecting. And I think Mayor Pete did a good job of connecting by speaking in a little more of a blunt fashion.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, there's two people that we haven't even mentioned in all of this in the A-block, and that is Cory Booker, the senator from New Jersey.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Mr. Nice Guy.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: He's the peacemaker.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The peacemaker, right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Blessed are the peacemakers. And Tom Steyer who was the billionaire that was on stage. He was looking directly into the camera. He had that tie that is just like, what? And I didn't know that he wears the same tie every day, but he has five of them.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He does?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's actually a tattoo.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: So, I think, the fact that he had made the debate stage totally irrelevant.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He makes Adam Schiff, you know, look conscious.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know, I think Amy Klobucher had a real good night.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Me, too.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I don't want us to run by her, because I think it's so interesting. She was directly taking on Elizabeth Warren in a way that suggested to me that she sees Warren as someone that she can beat in a straight on debate. But the whole business about how are you going to pay, let me just say, I think she's been very clear about how she wants to pay for health care in the country, which is she wants to impose a tax on the super rich. I don't think there's any question about that. It's just that she won't admit that it may mean that you also increase some taxes on the middle class. Her argument, of course, is overall cost, deductible, premiums, will go down.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think the best ticket from that group is Klobuchar, Mayor Pete.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, but remember --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No, no, no. Greg, on a bumper sticker, you can't have Buttigieg and Klobuchar.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Klobuchar and Buttigieg.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Either one.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Coming up, Joe Biden tries to explain away the Ukraine controversy. Plus, tempers flying in the Capital as we're learning of an explosive meeting between the president, Pelosi and Chuck Schumer, breaking news out of Washington, D.C., up next.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Former Vice President Joe Biden walked through his son's Ukraine controversy practically unscaled last night as debate moderators lobe multiple softballs questions. Watch this.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: President Trump has falsely accused your son of doing something wrong while serving on a company board in Ukraine. I want to point out, there's no evidence of wrongdoing by either one of you.

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN, FORMER U.S. VICE PRESIDENT
utterances.utterance: My son did nothing wrong. I did nothing wrong. I carried out the policy of the United States government in rooting out corruption in Ukraine. But I wanted to make a point about -- my son's statement speaks for itself. What we have to do now is focus on Donald Trump. He's going after me, because he knows if I get the nomination, I will beat him like a drum.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: And from bad to worse, Joe Biden has reportedly spent more than he raised in the third quarter of 2019. Juan, I would like to start with you. So notwithstanding the intro and the lack of follow-up that Anderson Cooper displayed, he did ask Joe Biden, pointblank, if it's not OK for the president to have his children be in foreign business dealings, why is it OK for the vice president? I put that question to you.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I think he answered it pretty clearly. He said he didn't have the discussions. Now, we've seen reporting that in any case there was some discussion, but he said no, and he said the son said no, and he says he stands by what the son had to say, which was awkward on the day of the debate for the son to come out. But, anyway, that's what happened. And he says he stands by what the son had to say, and he did nothing wrong. Anderson Cooper, by the way, I don't know why you're picking on him. It was a false accusation that was made against Biden, and now you have a situation where people are saying, oh, Joe Biden respond to this, respond to this. Well, he just said, flat out, hey, I'm not playing that game and I appreciated it. I think that he was strong not to play somebody else's game. The real debate today, it seems to me is up on the Hill where you have -- I think it was 130 Republicans voting against Trump on the pull-out from -- I mean, that's the real argument. That and the --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: How about the debate, Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, I'm saying, that's what -- it's not about -- this stuff about Biden is just a false --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know what's really bad for Joe Biden right now? President -- the former President Obama just endorsed Justin Trudeau before he endorsed Joe Biden who is, right now, he's been seen running to Walmart buying shoe polish.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: All right, Jesse, if Biden makes it to the general is this going to be the clip that haunts him that President Trump pulled is that you can't even answer the question.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I don't know if he's going to make it to the general. But I do remember in 2016 when CNN moderators would argue with the Republicans running for president. And now, they just team up and let them say whatever they want. You know what reminds me of? When someone was falsely accused of something without any evidence? Donald Trump was falsely accused of being a Russian colluder without any evidence. CNN never has actually said that Donald Trump was falsely accused without any evidence after two and a half years. So, that is funny and that's a perfect example of media bias. Also interesting, let's just switch the names because I'm going to start doing this just for fun. Imagine the minute Trump selected, Don Jr. gets a sweetheart deal on the board of a Ukrainian gas company, and then the president demands the guy investigating the corrupt Ukrainian gas company is fired and withhold aids, and then the guy gets fired. And then when they ask about him about it, you guys talked about it, they say no. We never brought it up. And by the way, I was just doing my job. Look elsewhere. Do you think the media would accept Donald Trump's and Don Jr. explanation for that? Absolutely not, and that's why it's so crooked. And the fact that Biden comes out and tells CNN that his job in Ukraine was to root out corruption, OK? Well, then your son goes and joins the board of the most corrupt gas company in Ukraine? They fire the prosecutor looking into the corrupt gas company. And, as a matter of fact, corruption in Ukraine increased under Joe Biden's watch. That's why Zelensky was elected. He ran on an anti-corruption platform.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Wow, Alice in Wonderland, you've got nothing on Jesse Watters. Way down the rabbit hole. You make stuff up --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What did I say that was wrong?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, what did you say that was wrong?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Can you just do it later?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: The fundraising thing, right. So he has spent more money than he has raise. And other candidates -- I think four other candidates have more cash on hand than he does. So he's got to figure out a way to step on the gas or reduce his burn rate. I do think that last night in the debate that one of the things that Democrats have learned is that attacking each other on stage doesn't work, or at least it doesn't work for long. Kamala Harris went after Joe Biden in that first debate, and she was popular for about 26 hours. Julian Castro went after Biden, and that last for 26 hours. So they're very happy to allow Donald Trump to be the one that beats up on Joe Biden, because then they don't have to. I do think for Biden, he could pull a Newt Gingrich and just go after the moderators, Juan. I think you'll remember that. And then that becomes the story, like, I've had it with you. I can't take it anymore. The other thing is Biden doesn't do any one-on-one interviews, so there's not a lot of ways to be able to dig in a little bit deeper. I mean, his son did an interview before he did.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Interesting. Greg, you feel so strongly about media bias.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I do. Thank you for bringing that up, Emily.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Thanks for noticing.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. I think that Anderson -- that was a pretty soft question for him. I would say it was up there with, maybe, you know, giving questions to a candidate. But the thing is, Biden, I just -- it's not if he drops out, it's when. To me, this grumpy smile that he has, and that orchestrated attempt at arousing climax at the end, you could see it coming and you felt that the sympathy clap was like a nurse -- you know, clapping for gramps because he finished the peas. I think that -- I think that he's misunderstanding the moment. He's seeing this as politics as usual and -- this moment has passed him.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It's not 2012.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's not 2012.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: I felt like in that moment he was a dad, and we saw him as that -- in the other side of trauma, and so it made sense that he's basically, like, I will never disparage my son on the stage. But then it was a failed opportunity for him to act presidential and taking it a step further and pivoting and saying and here, let me tell you about my ethics plan that I have which he's talked about.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But by doing that admits that it was wrong.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I just want to remind everybody, Joe Biden remains either in the lead or tied, basically, with Elizabeth Warren.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Hillary Clinton was once was.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: All right, up next, tempers flying in the nation's capital and the meeting between President Trump, Nancy Pelosi, and Chuck Schumer. This all just went down, we have the breaking details next.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Breaking news out of Washington. An explosive meeting in Washington as Nancy Pelosi and Chuck Schumer reportedly walked out of a meeting with President Trump, the topic at hand, Syria. According to top Democrats, Trump called Pelosi a third-rate politician. Here to break it all down, Kevin Corke. Kevin, earlier today, I said, well, we'll get back to you if anything big happens at the White House, and here you are. Tell us what happened.

utterances.speaker: KEVIN CORKE, FOX NEWS CORRESPONDENT
utterances.utterance: And there you have it, right? Well done, and that's a Colorado connection, get it done for you there on THE FIVE. Let me just say this, the White House says the president was measured, decisive, and factual. They called the walkout by Nancy Pelosi baffling, but not surprising. As for Pelosi, herself, well, her colleagues say the president was downright insulting. He was having a meltdown. Here's what Chuck Schumer said about it not long ago.

utterances.speaker: SEN. CHUCK SCHUMER (D-NY)
utterances.utterance: It was insulting, particularly to the Speaker. She kept her cool completely. But he called her a third-rate politician. He said that there are communists involved and you guys might like that. I mean, this was not a dialogue. It was sort of a diatribe, a nasty diatribe not focused on the facts.

utterances.speaker: CORKE
utterances.utterance: Fair and balance, that's the Democrats' side of things. On the GOP side, they say the Speaker didn't really have an intention of listening or contributing to this issue. She just wanted to have her way. Here's Mr. McCarthy.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: You see a pattern of behavior with Speaker Nancy Pelosi. She storms out of another meeting, trying to make it unproductive. The other Democrats, they actually had a very productive meeting.

utterances.speaker: CORKE
utterances.utterance: And you probably know this, Dana, there was actually another meeting scheduled for tomorrow about Syria. That meeting has been canceled, we are told. And given what happened today, probably not the worst idea. Dana?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right. Thanks, Kevin Corke at the White House. You have a third-rate politician as a compliment?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, somebody called me a third-rate -- it's better to be a first-rate politician. A first-rate politician, you're just a phony jack ass. But like -- Trump is a 12th rate politician. He doesn't even register, so it's actually a compliment. Look, this is obviously the worst thing that has ever happened since yesterday when the worst thing that ever happened had happened, and then before that. The fact is, every day with these people, it's the worst thing. Their hair is on fire all the time. You can see it from space. They're smoky heads are flaming. I don't care about it anymore. You can disagree with them about this. A lot of people do, you know. But the fact is this is who Trump is. He's America's cabdriver. He believes that -- like, if you ask him, if you go - - driving a cab and the cab driver go, this Middle East business it's a bunch of crap. What are we doing there? We're there for 20, 40 years. No one gets anything done. It's terrible. That's our president. What's wrong with that?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I tell you that's scary.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, it's actually --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, because he want -- you want somebody as your leader. Someone who protects the flock, someone who's wise, and someone --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He wants American troops out of harms way.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: In fact, he's creating more risk. Why do you think -- wait a second. Normally, on this show, we have sort of debate about things that are Republican, Democrat, conservative, liberal, libertarian, whatever. But, Greg, this is like 129 Republicans today voting with Democrats, including all of the House Republican leadership, to say the president is wrong, putting us Americans right here at home at risk, ISIS people being released to the world without any control.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think they have his best interest in mind in the criticism and the pushback.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: For me, I think it's like one of those things in the swamp when there's bipartisan consensus to stay in Syria, and then outside and the rest of the country there's consensus to get the hell out of Syria. That's the disconnect. And the president is looking at both parties who've made a mess in the Middle East. You've got the Arab spring. You've had genocides. You've had wars. You've got everything going on, a migration crisis, weapons of mass destruction, and he's gonna say, you know what, enough. Let's let the Turks fight the Kurds fight the Syrians fight the Iranians, and let's get the hell out of here.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Except for now he is trying to figure out that diplomacy piece, which I think that you could agree. Let's get out. But maybe just trying to figure out a way to do it that is a little bit less bloodshed.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Thank you, Ms. Perino.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: People are dying in Syria and Turkey and everywhere, including our--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: And New York City, by the way.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: And my tax dollars are paying the salary for those people who are sitting there and storming out of meetings and calling themselves insulting in front of the cameras like it's two little kids or three kids. No, he didn't. No, he did it, mom. I don't care. I want them to figure it out, because these are high stakes, in my opinion. And as a taxpayer, these are lives. So, I'm so sick of this civil war happening and the insulting from the coequal branch of government. We pay them and we put our faith in them to hold these offices to come to a consensus. This is getting out of control, in my opinion.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But how do you argue with the cab driver, Emily? If that cab driver is saying, no, just get out.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You're missing the point.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: That cab driver has been driving--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You're deliberately missing the point. All right. So, here's the debate that's going on that we saw today. You have a group of people that see the potential to hurt Trump in this thing. And so, they're building it up. Right. This is another thing. Remember, last week it was impeachment. Now, it's this. They'll find something else. So, I view a lot of this with this fight with suspicion. And there is actually a legitimate point that Trump is making and has been making for almost 20 years.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But what I'm saying to you is that the Republicans have largely stayed with President Trump in opposition to the impeachment. But we see something different here, Greg and I think it suggests, this is far more serious.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Can I make a historical comparison. You don't have to go back too far to when President Obama decided not to enforce the red line. And I don't know what the number was, but I bet it was at least 130 Democrats who said President Obama that is a terrible idea. You had three Cabinet secretaries, Clinton, Podesta and Gates all write books saying, and Carrie.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All saying that was not a good decision. That was a terrible decision, because it led to ISIS. So, it's not like this is unprecedented.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Right. But I think the difference here, Dana, is the President apparently is telling reporters, those Kurds who were our allies and who died in our fight, there are no angels. There's a lot of sand over there.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: There is a complicated issue with Kurds. That's all with everybody.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But you've got to stand by people who fight with you.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: At some point, you've got to go home.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What happened to the South Vietnamese. Remember what happened there? We've got the hell out of there. We left that whole country.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: That's not a good--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What did Barack Obama do in Iraq. They left Iraq.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: That's a really bad example.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: That's a terrible example.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: My point is, is that he doesn't want Americans to die. If other people want to fight and kill each other, which they've been doing thousands of years--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But now, he says he doesn't want them to. He just sent a letter to Erdogan saying, don't be a fool.
